Lastly, I may mention the name of Dr. Arthur
Schnitzler, son of the eminent laryngologist of bygone
days. Dr. Schnitzler was far better known, of course,
for his literary and poetical works than for his
medical achievements. Apart from his early coöpera¬
tion with his brother-in-law, Prof. Hajek—the present
chief of the clinic for rhinolaryngology in Vienna—he
took a great interest in psycho-analysis, even long
before Freud published his researches. The poet¬
physician, as Schnitzler may be termed, applied
intuitively the elements of analysis in his well-known
plays and dramas, some of which won for him the
